<p align='center'><font color='#0e024d' face='Arial'><strong>POTTERY INFORMATION</strong></font></p>

<p align='center'><font color='#0e024d' face='Arial'><small><b><small>|&nbsp; <a href='pottery_ow.asp'>Overview</a> &nbsp; |&nbsp; <a href='pottery_trivials.asp'>Trivial
Chart</a> &nbsp; |&nbsp; <a href='pottery_table.asp'>Pottery Item Table</a> &nbsp;
|&nbsp; <a href='pottery_vendors.asp'>Pottery Vendors</a>&nbsp; |</small></b></small></font></p>
<hr size='1' width='90%'>
<div align='center'><center>

<table border='0' width='90%'>
  <tr>
    <td valign='top' align='left'><font FACE='Tahoma' SIZE='2'></font><font size='4'><font color='#0E024D'><font face='Arial'>Overview</font></font><p></font><font SIZE='2'><font face='Arial'>One of the greatest things about pottery is that a lot of the items you make
    can be used in other trade skills (tinkering/baking/poison making). Also another thing
    good about pottery is that it is one of the cheaper trade skills to do, only requiring
    anywhere from 10 to 30pp to become a master (skill 100) in the skill. Becoming a grand
    master of a skill greater than 160 will require less than 50pp as long as you know what
    you are doing. </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'>Pottery used to start yielding profit around a skill of 70 or so by
    selling the finished product back to the vendors, but since the last patch (near the start
    of August, 1999) pottery does not become profitable until around a skill of 120 because of
    several reasons. Most of, if not all of the items a potter can make will yield a negative
    profit if you sell them back to the vendors now. The only items that are profitable now
    are the high skill poison vials, which you have to sell to other players to make a profit.
    </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'>There is a near zero player demand for the low skill items, but high
    level rogues are currently buying up the high skill vials from potters like mad. The steps
    to take to become a master potter have changed as well since the patch. </font></p>
    <p></font><font face='Arial' size='3' color='#0E024D'><strong>Making an Item</strong></font><font SIZE='2'></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'>With pottery there are 2 stages in creating a finished product. The
    first stage is combining the sketch/clay/water/other together on the potter&#146;s wheel.
    The second stage is to take the unfinished item created and fire it in a kiln with a
    firing sheet(s).</font></font></p>
    <font SIZE='2'><p><font face='Arial'>In order to maximize profit and minimize cost, some
    players create a &quot;mule&quot; character. These characters are made solely to be a
    tradesman/woman. Most people pick enchanters with their high <strong>Intelligence</strong>
    (increase skill faster), <strong>Wisdom</strong> (reduce the number of failures) and <strong>Charisma
    </strong>(better prices).</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'>I for one did not do this because most of my business I get is when
    I am out on the battlefield and it will be too much of a bother to get the goods to my
    location (i.e. having to log and switch characters and bring the other character to where
    I am).&nbsp; Also vendors will only buy <strong>completed </strong>items, they will not
    buy unfired items.</font></p>
    <p></font><font face='Arial' size='3' color='#0E024D'><strong>Skill Building</strong></font><font SIZE='2'></p>
    <p><font face='Arial'>Only place one point into pottery at your guild to get you started.
    You can put more than one point in, but pottery skill rises fast. Do medium jars till
    about skill level 45 or so. Remember: if it gives a message that this item is trivial for
    your skill to make when you are making it on the potter&#146;s wheel it is time to move to
    the next item. Do medium bowls till 122 in skill. It is recommended to destroy unfinished
    medium bowls rather than buy 2 high quality firing sheets in order to fire the bowl
    because firing will not increase your skill plus the 2 high quality sheets cost way more
    than the finished product. Do mixing bowls till 128 and large bowls till 148.</font></font></td>
  </tr>
</table>

